Critical Temperature Optimization

M. Marchildon

Last compiled October 4, 2022

Critical Temperature \((T_c)\)

Precipitation data can come in the form of just that: “precipitation”, without information of whether it’s in the snow (solid) or rain (liquid) form. A simple solution would be to determine a “critical” temperature \((T_c)\) from which precipitation falls either as snow or rain.

\[ \text{Rainfall}= \begin{cases} \text{Precipitation}, & T_a>T_c\\ 0 & \text{otherwise}, \end{cases} \]

\[ \text{Snowfall}= \begin{cases} \text{Precipitation}, & T_a\leq T_c\\ 0 & \text{otherwise}. \end{cases} \]

\(T_a\) is air temperature measured at land surface and is assumed to have some relationship with the temperature of the surface boundary layer. Here, it is discussed how an optimal \(T_c\) is determined for every ORMGP subwatershed.

Data Collected

6-hourly Precipitation

  • Composite CaPA-RPDA 6-hourly precipitation \((P)\) accumulation distributed at 10-15km grids are interpolated to 2,183 10km² sub-watersheds.
  • Exported 202009301300-CaPA-RDPA.nc from ORMGP-FEWS:
float precipitation_amount(time=27392, stations=2813);
  :long_name = "precipitation_amount";
  :units = "mm";
  :_FillValue = -9999.0f; // float
  :coordinates = "lat lon";

Period of record: 
  start date: 2001-12-31 19:00:00 -0500 EST
  end date: 2020-09-30 14:00:00 -0400 EDT
  (6-hourly)

Results

At the 6-hourly time step, at every sub-watershed, \(T_c\) is determined by computing:

\[ P_S= \begin{cases} P, & T_a\leq T_c\\ 0 & \text{otherwise} \end{cases} \]

for every season (i.e., water year), such that:

\[ \sum P_S \to \sum P_M \] for every water year. This results in 53,447 separate \(T_c\) optimizations averaging 5.1°C, with a mean residual/error \(\left(\left|\sum P_S - \sum P_M \right|\right)\) of 3.5 mm, roughly 0.3% of annual average precipitation. Below are this distributions of the results.

Seasonally, there does appear to be a ~6-year oscillation around the mean, even after 2011, when the SNODAS data are used:

Discussion

Overall, regional \(T_c\) managed to remain close to the freezing point as expected. There are some rare outliers, hover all seem to converge to negligible residuals. Based on these results, the CaPA-RDPA precipitation field are parsed into the \(P_R\) and \(P_S\) components at the 6-hour timestep, then aggregated to daily timesteps.
